---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-requirements', text: 'Visa Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { text: 'Uruguay for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/uruguay' },
  { text: 'Brazil for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/brazil' },
  { text: 'Mexico for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/mexico' },
  { text: 'Spain for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/spain' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'maxAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage Type' },
  { key: 'argentinaNetwork', header: 'Argentina Network' },
  { key: 'currencyNote', header: 'Premium Currency' },
  { key: 'annualCost', header: 'Annual Cost (65yo)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Comprehensive', argentinaNetwork: 'Hospital Italiano, Hospital Alemán, Swiss Medical', currencyNote: 'USD (stable)', annualCost: '$4,500-7,200' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Premium', argentinaNetwork: 'Major private facilities', currencyNote: 'USD (stable)', annualCost: '$5,500-9,000' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Comprehensive', argentinaNetwork: 'Good coverage', currencyNote: 'EUR/USD (stable)', annualCost: '$4,200-7,000' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'US-focused expat', argentinaNetwork: 'Limited direct', currencyNote: 'USD (stable)', annualCost: '$6,500-10,500' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', maxAge: '74', coverage: 'Flexible', argentinaNetwork: 'Reimbursement', currencyNote: 'USD (stable)', annualCost: '$3,500-6,000' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense Category' },
  { key: 'pesoPrice', header: 'Peso Price' },
  { key: 'usdEstimate', header: 'USD Estimate*' },
  { key: 'note', header: 'Note' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance', pesoPrice: 'N/A', usdEstimate: '$3,500-9,000/year', note: 'Premiums in USD provide stability' },
  { category: 'Private GP Visit', pesoPrice: 'ARS 15,000-30,000', usdEstimate: '$15-30', note: 'Extremely affordable' },
  { category: 'Specialist Consultation', pesoPrice: 'ARS 25,000-50,000', usdEstimate: '$25-50', note: 'World-class specialists' },
  { category: 'Hospital Day (Private)', pesoPrice: 'ARS 150,000-300,000', usdEstimate: '$150-300', note: 'Premium facilities' },
  { category: 'MRI Scan', pesoPrice: 'ARS 80,000-150,000', usdEstimate: '$80-150', note: '80% less than US' },
  { category: 'Prepaga (local plan)', pesoPrice: 'ARS 50,000-150,000/month', usdEstimate: '$50-150/month', note: 'Varies by plan/age' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Argentina | Expat Guide 2025"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees and seniors in Argentina. Compare international providers, understand currency considerations, and plan your South American retirement."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Argentina"
  subheadline="Your guide to world-class healthcare at incredible value in South America's cultural capital"
  heroImage="/images/countries/argentina-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
>
  <section id="overview" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Overview</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentina offers a compelling—if complex—retirement proposition: world-class private healthcare at a fraction of US or European prices, sophisticated European-influenced culture, stunning natural beauty from Patagonia to wine country, and a cost of living that rewards those with foreign income. Buenos Aires alone would justify consideration, but Argentina offers much more.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      For seniors with USD, EUR, or other stable currency income, Argentina can be remarkably affordable. The peso's ongoing devaluation means foreign currency stretches further each year. Healthcare that costs $150,000 in the US might cost $15,000 in Buenos Aires at a world-class facility. This reality makes Argentina a medical tourism destination for South Americans and increasingly for North Americans.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Buenos Aires hosts medical facilities that rival the best in the world. Hospital Italiano, Hospital Alemán, and Hospital Británico are internationally accredited institutions with specialists trained at top global centers. Mendoza offers excellent wine country retirement with good regional healthcare. Patagonia attracts adventurous retirees, though medical resources are more limited.
    </p>
    <p>
      The caveat is complexity: currency volatility, inflation, and periodic economic crises require adaptability. Those who learn to navigate Argentina's quirks find exceptional value and quality of life. Those expecting First World predictability may find it frustrating. The rewards are significant for the right person.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="healthcare-system" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentina operates a three-tier healthcare system: public hospitals (free but overcrowded), obras sociales (union-based health insurance), and prepagas (private health insurance). The private sector is where Argentina truly excels, with some facilities ranking among the best in the Americas.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Buenos Aires concentrates Argentina's medical excellence. Hospital Italiano, founded in 1853, is Argentina's leading academic medical center with internationally recognized programs in oncology, cardiology, transplants, and neurology. Hospital Alemán provides German-standard care with strong orthopedics and cardiac programs. Hospital Británico, Sanatorio Otamendi, and Swiss Medical facilities round out the premium options.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      The prepaga system offers private health insurance from organizations like Swiss Medical, OSDE, Galeno, and Medicus. These provide comprehensive coverage for monthly fees that seem impossibly low to foreign eyes—often $100-200/month for coverage that would cost $1,000+ elsewhere. The catch: peso-denominated premiums mean prices quoted today will be different tomorrow.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Medical tourism is a growing industry, with Argentines explicitly marketing to foreign patients. Plastic surgery, dental work, cardiac procedures, and orthopedics attract patients from throughout the Americas. This infrastructure benefits resident expats through competitive pricing and quality consciousness.
    </p>
    <p>
      Spanish proficiency is essential outside international patient departments. While premium hospitals have English-speaking coordinators, day-to-day medical interactions require Spanish. Many doctors speak English, but the supporting infrastructure assumes Spanish.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="visa-requirements" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Visa Options for Senior Expats</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentina has one of the most welcoming immigration policies in Latin America. The country offers straightforward residency for those with retirement income, and the process—while bureaucratic—is achievable without significant obstacles.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Pensionado (Retiree) Visa</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      The pensionado visa requires proof of monthly pension income of at least $500 USD (yes, the threshold is low by international standards). This provides 1-year temporary residency, renewable annually. After 3 years of temporary residence, permanent residence is available. The low income threshold reflects Argentina's desire to attract immigrants.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Rentista (Income from Investments)</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Similar to pensionado but for those without traditional pensions. Requires demonstration of stable income from investments, rental properties, or other sources outside Argentina. Same $500/month minimum applies, with permanent residence available after 3 years.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Perpetual Tourist (Not Recommended)</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Some foreigners live in Argentina long-term on tourist status by crossing to Uruguay or Chile every 90 days. This is technically legal but provides no pathway to residency, complicates banking and renting, and leaves you without legal protection. Given Argentina's easy residency process, formal residence is strongly recommended.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Required Documents</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-1">
      <li>Valid passport</li>
      <li>Birth certificate (apostilled and translated)</li>
      <li>Criminal background check from home country (apostilled, translated)</li>
      <li>Proof of income (pension statements, notarized letters)</li>
      <li>Argentine address</li>
      <li>Medical certificate (from Argentine doctor)</li>
      <li>Application fee (varies, modest)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Health insurance is not officially required for residency but is highly recommended. Once resident, you can access public healthcare (free) or enroll in prepaga (private insurance). International insurance provides stability and premium access regardless of local options.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="insurance-requirements" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Insurance Requirements for Seniors</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentina's currency volatility makes insurance strategy particularly important. Peso-denominated coverage (prepagas) is affordable but unpredictable. Dollar-denominated international coverage provides stability but costs more in absolute terms.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">The Prepaga Option</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentine prepagas (OSDE, Swiss Medical, Galeno, Medicus) offer comprehensive private coverage at low dollar-equivalent prices. Monthly premiums of $100-200 USD provide access to premium hospitals. However, prices are set in pesos and adjust with inflation—what costs $150 today might cost $200 or more after an inflation adjustment next month.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Why International Insurance Makes Sense</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Currency stability:</strong> Premiums in USD/EUR don't fluctuate with Argentine peso</li>
      <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> Access to Uruguay, Brazil, Chile for alternative care</li>
      <li><strong>US access:</strong> Important for American expats; some conditions may warrant US treatment</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency evacuation:</strong> Exit option if Argentina's situation deteriorates</li>
      <li><strong>Guaranteed lifetime:</strong> Argentine prepagas may have age-related changes; international coverage continues</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Recommended Coverage Levels</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Overall maximum:</strong> $1-2 million (more than adequate for Argentina costs)</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital room:</strong> Private room at premium hospitals</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency evacuation:</strong> $100,000+ for transport to US or other countries</li>
      <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> Uruguay and Brazil access valuable</li>
      <li><strong>Currency:</strong> Premiums in USD essential for planning stability</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Hybrid Strategy</h3>
    <p>
      Many expats combine approaches: prepaga for routine care and local hospital access, plus international insurance (higher deductible) for major events, regional access, and currency stability. If prepagas become too expensive or unreliable, international coverage remains. This approach typically costs $3,000-5,000/year total.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Find Your Argentina Coverage"
    description="Compare international health insurance plans with stable USD pricing. Protect against currency volatility while accessing Argentina's world-class private healthcare."
    buttonText="Compare Plans for Argentina"
    buttonHref="/get-quotes"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <section id="recommended-providers" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      International insurers offer USD-denominated premiums that shield you from peso volatility. Look for providers with Latin American networks and the ability to handle reimbursements if direct billing isn't available at your chosen Argentine facility.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Provider Insights</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Cigna Global</strong> has good Latin American coverage with relationships at major Buenos Aires hospitals. USD premiums provide stability. Direct billing may be available at Hospital Italiano and similar facilities; otherwise smooth reimbursement. Good all-around choice.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Bupa Global</strong> provides premium coverage with established Latin American presence. Higher cost but comprehensive benefits. USD premiums lock in your costs regardless of peso movements. Good for those wanting maximum coverage.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers solid Latin American coverage at competitive USD rates. Reliable claims processing whether direct billing or reimbursement. Well-suited for those seeking value.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>GeoBlue</strong> is ideal for American expats maintaining US ties. Blue Cross Blue Shield network in the US is unmatched. Argentine coverage works through reimbursement. Best for those who may return to US for certain care.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>IMG Global</strong> provides budget-friendly USD-denominated coverage. Argentine facilities primarily through reimbursement. Good catastrophic coverage option for those using prepagas for routine care.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Expected Healthcare Costs</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentina offers some of the best healthcare value in the world for those with foreign currency. Prices shown below are approximate USD equivalents—actual peso amounts change constantly with exchange rates and inflation. The key insight: high-quality care is extremely affordable in dollar terms.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-2 text-sm text-neutral-600">*USD estimates based on current exchange rates; actual costs vary with peso movements</p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-800 mb-3 mt-6">Insurance Strategy for Argentina</h3>
    <p class="mb-4">
      Argentina's low USD-equivalent costs make various strategies viable. The key is ensuring stable currency protection for your healthcare budget.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Prepaga-focused approach ($1,500-2,500/year):</strong> Enroll in quality prepaga (Swiss Medical, OSDE) for ~$150/month peso-equivalent. Accept currency risk for potential savings. Add minimal international coverage for travel and emergencies.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-4">
      <strong>Balanced approach ($4,500-6,500/year):</strong> International insurance with moderate deductible. Use for direct access to premium hospitals. May add prepaga for convenience. Currency-stable planning.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>USD-protected approach ($6,000-9,000/year):</strong> Comprehensive international insurance as primary coverage. Skip prepaga complexity. Full USD budgeting. Maximum predictability and flexibility.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Your Personalized Quote"
    description="Compare USD-denominated plans from multiple providers. Protect your healthcare budget from currency volatility while accessing Argentina's exceptional medical facilities."
    buttonText="Request Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/get-quotes"
  />

  <section id="scenarios" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Real-World Scenarios</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">
      These scenarios illustrate how different insurance setups perform for common situations seniors face in Argentina.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 1: Cardiac Surgery at Hospital Italiano</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 70-year-old needs coronary bypass surgery. At Hospital Italiano, one of Latin America's best cardiac centers, the procedure costs approximately $18,000-25,000 USD—versus $150,000+ in the US.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With international insurance: Full cardiac surgery at Hospital Italiano covered after $2,500 deductible. ICU stay, surgeon fees, rehabilitation included. World-class care at fraction of US cost, with currency-stable insurance covering the expense. Same quality, 85% savings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 2: Cancer Treatment Over 12 Months</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 68-year-old is diagnosed with colon cancer requiring surgery, chemotherapy, and follow-up. Complete treatment at Hospital Alemán totals approximately $35,000-50,000 over 12 months.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With comprehensive insurance: Full treatment at Hospital Alemán covered. Surgery, oncologist consultations, chemotherapy, imaging—all under same policy. Total out-of-pocket: deductible. International insurance provides currency stability through long treatment. Could alternatively seek treatment in US under same policy if preferred.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 3: Emergency During Mendoza Wine Country Visit</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 67-year-old visiting Mendoza wineries suffers a stroke. Regional hospital provides initial stabilization but comprehensive stroke care requires Buenos Aires transfer.
        </p>
        <p class="text-amber-700 font-medium">
          With international insurance including evacuation: Mendoza emergency care covered. Air ambulance to Hospital Italiano Buenos Aires ($15,000) covered. Comprehensive stroke treatment in world-class facility. Without evacuation coverage, would face challenging logistics and costs for urgent transfer. Regional coverage essential for those exploring Argentina.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 4: Hip Replacement Surgery</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 66-year-old needs total hip replacement. Argentine private hospitals quote $8,000-12,000 including implant, surgery, and hospital stay—versus $50,000+ in the US.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With prepaga enrollment: Hip replacement at prepaga's network hospital essentially free (copays only). Quality is good. Alternatively, international insurance covers procedure at Hospital Británico after deductible—premium facility with more amenities. Either approach delivers quality at fraction of US cost.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 5: Managing Multiple Chronic Conditions</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          A 71-year-old manages diabetes, hypertension, and arthritis requiring regular monitoring and medications.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With prepaga: Quarterly specialist visits covered with minimal copays. Medications through prepaga pharmacy at discounted peso prices. Annual management: under $500 USD equivalent. International insurance reserved for complications or if prepaga becomes unreliable. Currency savings on routine care, dollar protection for emergencies.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Scenario 6: Economic Crisis and Currency Collapse</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-3">
          During a severe economic crisis, peso loses 50% of value against dollar. Prepaga raises prices dramatically in peso terms. Local healthcare system experiences disruptions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-green-700 font-medium">
          With USD-denominated international insurance: Coverage continues unchanged at same dollar cost. Can access any private hospital regardless of prepaga chaos. Evacuation coverage provides exit option if necessary. This scenario has occurred before in Argentina—USD insurance provides crucial stability during crises.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-4">
      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Argentina's economic instability too risky for retirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          This depends on your tolerance and adaptability. Argentina has experienced multiple economic crises, high inflation, and currency volatility. For retirees with stable USD/EUR income and international health insurance, the practical impact is limited—your foreign income buys more during crises, and your healthcare remains covered. The risk is real for those relying on peso assets or local systems. Many expats thrive by keeping income and major commitments in hard currency.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does Argentina compare to Uruguay for retirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Argentina offers significantly lower costs (especially during peso weakness), larger expat community, more sophisticated culture and dining, and bigger city options. Uruguay offers stability, safety, simpler bureaucracy, and lower risk. Healthcare quality is comparable at the top tier in both. Argentina suits adventurous retirees comfortable with uncertainty; Uruguay suits those prioritizing predictability. Many expats consider both or move between them.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Should I get a prepaga or just use international insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Both approaches work. Prepagas provide excellent value and routine care convenience when stable. International insurance provides currency protection and crisis resilience. Many expats use both: prepaga for routine care and familiarity with local system; international insurance as stable backstop for major events and travel. If you must choose one, international insurance is safer for seniors due to age-related prepaga issues and currency protection.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Spanish necessary for healthcare?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Yes, for most interactions. Premium hospitals have international patient coordinators who speak English, and many doctors speak English. But pharmacists, administrative staff, and general practitioners often speak only Spanish. Buenos Aires is more English-friendly than provinces. Learning Spanish significantly improves healthcare navigation and quality of life. Many expats take Spanish classes upon arrival.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about medications and prescriptions?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Pharmacies are widespread and well-stocked. Prices in USD terms are extremely low—often 80-90% below US prices. Generic medications are common. Prepagas provide medication discounts at network pharmacies. Some medications require prescriptions that are easier to obtain elsewhere. Specialty drugs may need ordering but are available. Overall, medication access is excellent and affordable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the expat retirement community like?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">
          Buenos Aires has a substantial international community with Americans, Europeans, and others. The Palermo, Recoleta, and Belgrano neighborhoods host many expats. Facebook groups, expat clubs, language exchanges, and social organizations provide community. Outside Buenos Aires, expat presence is smaller—Mendoza has some wine-oriented expats, Patagonia attracts adventurous types. The community tends toward those comfortable with uncertainty who appreciate Argentina's unique offerings.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Argentine Retirement?"
    description="Get USD-denominated health insurance quotes from providers experienced with Latin America's most complex market. Protect your healthcare budget while accessing world-class Buenos Aires medicine."
    buttonText="Get Your Free Quote"
    buttonHref="/get-quotes"
    variant="highlight"
  />
</PageShell>
